            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this cholesterol calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool uses your standard lipid panel (Total Cholesterol,
                HDL, Triglycerides, and optional LDL) to estimate:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  LDL cholesterol (calculated by Friedewald or Martin/extended
                  method)
                </li>
                <li>Non‑HDL cholesterol (Total − HDL)</li>
                <li>Total/HDL and LDL/HDL ratios</li>
                <li>
                  Qualitative interpretation based on commonly used cut‑offs
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                It is designed for education and quick reference only and must
                not replace professional medical advice, diagnosis, or
                treatment.
              </p>

              <h2>Formulas used</h2>

              <h3>1. Unit conversion</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Cholesterol (mg/dL) → mmol/L</strong></p>
                <p>\(\text{mmol/L} = \dfrac{\text{mg/dL}}{38.67}\)</p>
                <p><strong>Triglycerides (mg/dL) → mmol/L</strong></p>
                <p>\(\text{mmol/L} = \dfrac{\text{mg/dL}}{88.57}\)</p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Friedewald LDL formula</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>In mg/dL (fasting sample, TG not very high):</p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{LDL}_{\text{Friedewald}} = \text{TC} - \text{HDL} -
                  \frac{\text{TG}}{5} \]
                </p>
                <p>In mmol/L (approximate):</p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{LDL} = \text{TC} - \text{HDL} - \frac{\text{TG}}{2.2}
                  \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The Friedewald equation is widely used but becomes unreliable
                when triglycerides are high (typically &gt; 400&nbsp;mg/dL or
                4.5&nbsp;mmol/L) or in non‑fasting samples with very recent
                high‑fat meals.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Martin / extended LDL estimation (simplified)</h3>
              <p>
                The Martin–Hopkins method refines the triglyceride divisor based
                on triglyceride and non‑HDL levels instead of using a fixed
                value of 5. In this calculator we approximate that approach by
                using:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>Let \(d\) be an adaptive divisor:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\(d = 6\) if TG &lt; 100 mg/dL</li>
                  <li>\(d = 5\) if 100 ≤ TG &lt; 150 mg/dL</li>
                  <li>\(d = 4.5\) if 150 ≤ TG &lt; 200 mg/dL</li>
                  <li>\(d = 4\) if 200 ≤ TG &lt; 300 mg/dL</li>
                  <li>\(d = 3.5\) if TG ≥ 300 mg/dL</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Then:</p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{LDL}_{\text{Martin}} \approx \text{TC} - \text{HDL} -
                  \frac{\text{TG}}{d} \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The original Martin–Hopkins method uses a detailed look‑up
                table; this simplified version captures the idea of a variable
                divisor while remaining transparent.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Non‑HDL cholesterol</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>\[ \text{Non‑HDL} = \text{TC} - \text{HDL} \]</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Non‑HDL cholesterol includes all atherogenic (potentially
                artery‑clogging) particles: LDL, VLDL, IDL, lipoprotein(a), and
                remnants. It often tracks cardiovascular risk better than LDL
                alone, especially when triglycerides are elevated.
              </p>

              <h3>5. Cholesterol ratios</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Total/HDL ratio</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{TC/HDL ratio} = \frac{\text{Total
                  Cholesterol}}{\text{HDL}} \]
                </p>
                <p><strong>LDL/HDL ratio</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{LDL/HDL ratio} = \frac{\text{LDL}}{\text{HDL}} \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Ratios help summarize the balance between “atherogenic” and
                “protective” lipoproteins. Lower ratios generally indicate lower
                cardiovascular risk.
              </p>

              <h2>Interpreting your results</h2>
              <p>
                Reference ranges vary slightly between guidelines and countries.
                The thresholds below are approximate and for adults:
              </p>

              <h3>LDL cholesterol (mg/dL)</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <span class="badge bg-green-100 text-green-800">Optimal</span>
                  &lt; 100
                </li>
                <li>
                  <span class="badge bg-emerald-100 text-emerald-800"
                    >Near optimal</span
                  >
                  100–129
                </li>
                <li>
                  <span class="badge bg-amber-100 text-amber-800"
                    >Borderline high</span
                  >
                  130–159
                </li>
                <li>
                  <span class="badge bg-orange-100 text-orange-800">High</span>
                  160–189
                </li>
                <li>
                  <span class="badge bg-red-100 text-red-800">Very high</span> ≥
                  190
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Non‑HDL cholesterol (mg/dL)</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Desirable: &lt; 130 (low–moderate risk)</li>
                <li>Often targeted &lt; 100 in high‑risk patients</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Cholesterol ratios</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Total/HDL ratio: ideal &lt; 4.0; higher values suggest
                  increased risk.
                </li>
                <li>
                  LDL/HDL ratio: often targeted &lt; 2.5; &gt; 3.5 may indicate
                  higher risk.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations and when to seek medical advice</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Calculated LDL is unreliable when triglycerides are very high,
                  in some genetic lipid disorders, or in non‑fasting samples
                  with recent heavy meals.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Cholesterol is only one part of cardiovascular risk; blood
                  pressure, smoking, diabetes, age, family history, and other
                  factors are also critical.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Only a qualified clinician can decide on treatment such as
                  lifestyle changes, statins, or other lipid‑lowering therapies.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Always discuss your results and any concerns with your doctor or
                lipid specialist.
              </p>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>Do I need to fast for this calculator?</h3>
              <p>
                Many modern guidelines accept non‑fasting lipid panels for
                routine screening. However, triglycerides can rise after meals,
                which may affect calculated LDL. If your triglycerides are high
                or results are borderline, your clinician may request a fasting
                repeat test.
              </p>

              <h3>Is LDL the only number that matters?</h3>
              <p>
                No. LDL is important, but non‑HDL cholesterol, apolipoprotein B,
                and overall cardiovascular risk scores (such as ASCVD risk
                estimators) can provide additional insight. This calculator
                focuses on standard lipid panel values that are widely
                available.
              </p>

              <h3>Can lifestyle changes improve my cholesterol?</h3>
              <p>
                Diet, physical activity, weight management, and smoking
                cessation can all improve lipid profiles for many people. Some
                individuals also need medication due to genetics or high
                baseline risk. Never start, stop, or change medication without
                medical supervision.
              </p>
